{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fcb1868f-5ffa-4a36-aadb-17900f7db1ea","content":"The project has a single file. Here's the scan result:\n\n### Static Dependency Report — `my_app/`\n\n| File | Line | Call | Risk |\n|------|------|------|------|\n| `views.py` | 3 | `datetime.now()` | 🔴 Hard to test |\n\n**1 untestable static found** in 1 file.\n\n---\n\n#### Why it's a problem\n`datetime.now()` returns the real clock time, making it impossible to assert on time-dependent output in tests.\n\n#### Recommended fix (Django-idiomatic)\nUse `django.utils.timezone.now` and mock it in tests:\n\n```python\nfrom django.utils import timezone\n\ndef index(request):\n    now = timezone.now()\n    return render(request, 'index.html', {'time': now})\n```\n\nThen in tests, use `freezegun` or `unittest.mock.patch`:\n```python\nfrom unittest.mock import patch\nfrom django.utils import timezone\n\n@patch('my_app.views.timezone.now')\ndef test_index(self, mock_now):\n    mock_now.return_value = datetime(2026, 1, 1)\n    # ... assertions with deterministic time\n```\n\nThis also gives you timezone-aware datetimes, which Django expects when `USE_TZ = True`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8a41b56d-de71-40af-820f-115a37c74df1","outputTokens":319,"requestId":"67C1:2D5697:1B2EB5D:1EB2EF7:69FD507C"},"id":"ddcac347-e12a-45a2-a760-ec103bc402d7","timestamp":"2026-05-08T02:55:00.360Z","parentId":"a06e1512-77bb-454e-9e6d-a7418b37e994"}
